1633
01:02:15,798 --> 01:02:18,534
so I'll make that, hoping
only good things will happen to Jun-young.

1634
01:02:18,601 --> 01:02:20,603
I'll only use the chicken wings
and stuff them.

1635
01:02:20,670 --> 01:02:22,238
-So that's one.
-Just the wings?

1636
01:02:22,305 --> 01:02:25,108
I often eat wonton noodles
and wonton soup in Hong Kong,

1637
01:02:25,174 --> 01:02:27,510
so I'll make the wontons for the soup.

1638
01:02:27,577 --> 01:02:30,079
Instead of dumpling skin,
I'm going to use radish.

1639
01:02:30,146 --> 01:02:32,048
-Radish dumpling.
-Will you have enough time?

1640
01:02:32,115 --> 01:02:35,885
-I'd like to present those healthy dishes.
-Can you make both of those?

1641
01:02:35,952 --> 01:02:40,556
Then let us begin
the 15-minute cook-off right now.

1642
01:02:40,623 --> 01:02:43,793
Here to become a Parisienne today,

1643
01:02:43,860 --> 01:02:45,428
Chef Amy Park.

1644
01:02:45,495 --> 01:02:49,065
Willing to lose his good vibes
to become the crazy one today,

1645
01:02:49,132 --> 01:02:51,434
Chef Son Jong-won.

1646
01:02:51,501 --> 01:02:54,437
The first body swap round
here at <i>Chef & My Fridge!</i>

1647
01:02:54,504 --> 01:02:57,740
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1648
01:02:58,374 --> 01:02:59,542
Let's go!

1649
01:02:59,609 --> 01:03:01,110
You two have swapped bodies.

1650
01:03:01,477 --> 01:03:03,212
BODIES SWAPPED!

1651
01:03:03,279 --> 01:03:04,714
You have to swap bodies.

1652
01:03:04,781 --> 01:03:06,783
-You must become each other.
-Hurry up.

1653
01:03:06,849 --> 01:03:08,451
Son Jong-won becomes Amy Park.

1654
01:03:08,518 --> 01:03:09,352
-And vice versa.
-What's that?

1655
01:03:09,418 --> 01:03:11,053
-I'm now…
-She's actually measuring it!

1656
01:03:11,120 --> 01:03:12,955
-She's using a scale.
-She's measuring.

1657
01:03:13,022 --> 01:03:15,424
I think she's trying to make tuiles.

1658
01:03:15,491 --> 01:03:16,793
This is Jun-young's scale.

1659
01:03:16,859 --> 01:03:19,796
-That's Jun-young's.
-It's Jun-young's scale.

1660
01:03:19,862 --> 01:03:21,197
You never use that in Chinese cuisine.

1661
01:03:21,264 --> 01:03:24,167
You measure stuff with a ladle instead.
Like counting how many scoops.

1662
01:03:24,233 --> 01:03:25,368
-Yes.
-Yes.

1663
01:03:25,434 --> 01:03:27,470
That's why they can move much faster.

1664
01:03:27,537 --> 01:03:29,806
But if she does that,
it'll surely take longer.

1665
01:03:30,673 --> 01:03:33,576
She's now using a beaker

1666
01:03:33,643 --> 01:03:38,314
and a bottle engraved with measurements.

1667
01:03:38,381 --> 01:03:41,417
It's like chemistry class.
Is that going to explode?

1668
01:03:41,484 --> 01:03:43,019
Don't cook that over high heat.

1669
01:03:43,085 --> 01:03:44,887
No, lower the heat.

1670
01:03:46,155 --> 01:03:47,890
HIGH HEAT

1671
01:03:47,957 --> 01:03:49,692
No, don't squeeze now!

1672
01:03:49,759 --> 01:03:50,660
Are you making tuiles?

1673
01:03:50,726 --> 01:03:52,328
-I am.
-Not now.

1674
01:03:52,395 --> 01:03:54,564
-That'll turn into <i>jeonbyeong</i>.
-Yes.

1675
01:03:54,630 --> 01:03:56,299
She's making <i>jeonbyeong</i>.

1676
01:03:56,365 --> 01:03:58,267
Drop an egg,
and it becomes egg bread, right?

1677
01:03:58,968 --> 01:04:00,670
UNBOTHERED

1678
01:04:01,304 --> 01:04:03,105
SQUEEZING THE BATTER OUT, UNSHAKEN

1679
01:04:04,040 --> 01:04:05,608
That's good.

1680
01:04:05,675 --> 01:04:06,642
CONTINUING WITH VIGOR

1681
01:04:06,709 --> 01:04:08,611
They're turning into tuiles.

1682
01:04:08,678 --> 01:04:10,079
Don't add too much batter.

1683
01:04:10,146 --> 01:04:10,980
She's fierce.

1684
01:04:11,047 --> 01:04:13,282
A couple of those
will turn into <i>jeonbyeong</i>.

1685
01:04:13,349 --> 01:04:14,750
WILL THEY TURN INTO TUILES?

1686
01:04:15,184 --> 01:04:17,153
WHAT ABOUT JONG-WON WITH EUN-YEONG'S SOUL?

1687
01:04:18,154 --> 01:04:20,890
So he's only using the wings?

1688
01:04:20,957 --> 01:04:24,360
He said he'd use the wings
to make eight-treasure chicken.

1689
01:04:24,427 --> 01:04:26,662
The key is to stuff them
without letting them tear.

1690
01:04:26,729 --> 01:04:28,731
How will he fit eight ingredients inside?

1691
01:04:28,798 --> 01:04:30,166
Right?

1692
01:04:30,233 --> 01:04:32,501
-The wings seem small.
-He has to remove the bones properly.

1693
01:04:32,568 --> 01:04:34,837
If it tears apart, it's over.

1694
01:04:34,904 --> 01:04:36,906
May I use this?

1695
01:04:36,973 --> 01:04:38,241
Take it.

1696
01:04:38,307 --> 01:04:39,775
-Give me the bones after.
-Okay.

1697
01:04:39,842 --> 01:04:42,478
-She steals the chicken.
-Yes, I need it too.

1698
01:04:42,545 --> 01:04:45,181
-I see. Jong-won is using just the wings?
-Just the wings?

1699
01:04:46,015 --> 01:04:46,983
SCRAPE

1700
01:04:47,049 --> 01:04:48,885
He's good at removing the bone cleanly.

1701
01:04:49,385 --> 01:04:51,687
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

1702
01:04:51,754 --> 01:04:53,589
He removed the bones.

1703
01:04:53,656 --> 01:04:56,225
"I'll remove your flesh from your bones."

1704
01:04:56,893 --> 01:04:59,028
That took about two minutes.

1705
01:04:59,562 --> 01:05:01,530
AMY PREPS THE CHICKEN TOO!

1706
01:05:02,999 --> 01:05:04,800
SLIPS

1707
01:05:05,401 --> 01:05:06,502
This isn't going to work.

1708
01:05:07,403 --> 01:05:09,105
She grabbed the Chinese knife!

1709
01:05:09,171 --> 01:05:11,073
-What?
-Hey, what are you doing?

1710
01:05:11,140 --> 01:05:13,209
-What is that, Eun-yeong?
-What are you doing?

1711
01:05:13,276 --> 01:05:15,678
-That's Chinese chili chicken!
-It's not!

1712
01:05:15,745 --> 01:05:17,513
You're making
Chinese chili chicken right now!

1713
01:05:17,780 --> 01:05:19,749
THE COMPLAINTS CONTINUE, SO…

1714
01:05:19,815 --> 01:05:20,816
<i>Bonjour.</i>

1715
01:05:20,883 --> 01:05:21,984
<i>Bonjour.</i>

1716
01:05:22,051 --> 01:05:23,052
"<i>Bonjour</i>"?

1717
01:05:24,954 --> 01:05:27,089
THE SUDDEN MORNING GREETING

1718
01:05:27,156 --> 01:05:29,158
I guess she doesn't speak Korean.

1719
01:05:29,225 --> 01:05:31,093
-Chinatown.
-She's only using French.

1720
01:05:31,160 --> 01:05:32,762
-What?
-Chinatown.

1721
01:05:32,828 --> 01:05:35,831
Why are you saying that?
"Chinatown" is English.

1722
01:05:35,898 --> 01:05:38,067
-There's one in Paris.
-Chinatown in Paris.

1723
01:05:38,134 --> 01:05:39,402
I guess you didn't know.

1724
01:05:40,136 --> 01:05:41,537
She's seriously a wacko.

1725
01:05:42,138 --> 01:05:44,106
JONG-WON USES A CHINESE KNIFE TOO!

1726
01:05:45,274 --> 01:05:47,843
He's good with a Chinese knife.

1727
01:05:47,910 --> 01:05:49,445
MEETING THE FINE DINING SIZE REQUIREMENT

1728
01:05:49,512 --> 01:05:51,147
My knife works so well.

1729
01:05:51,213 --> 01:05:53,015
That's how you actually use that knife.

1730
01:05:53,082 --> 01:05:55,484
I never knew it worked so well.

1731
01:05:55,551 --> 01:05:57,320
He stays true to the topic.

1732
01:05:57,386 --> 01:05:59,588
Jun-young has his eyes on everything.

1733
01:05:59,655 --> 01:06:01,791
Poong, your knife works well.

1734
01:06:01,857 --> 01:06:03,426
It does work well.

1735
01:06:03,492 --> 01:06:06,429
-It never worked when you used it.
-It never worked with me.

1736
01:06:08,064 --> 01:06:09,332
Wait, what?

1737
01:06:09,398 --> 01:06:11,033
USING A CHINESE KNIFE TO PREP CHICKEN

1738
01:06:11,100 --> 01:06:12,702
She's using the Chinese knife again.

1739
01:06:12,768 --> 01:06:13,836
Chinatown.

1740
01:06:14,971 --> 01:06:16,072
REVISITS CHINATOWN

1741
01:06:16,138 --> 01:06:17,173
What now?

1742
01:06:17,239 --> 01:06:20,977
That's not even French. That's English!

1743
01:06:21,043 --> 01:06:22,578
<i>Merci beaucoup.</i>

1744
01:06:24,046 --> 01:06:26,215
-"<i>Merci beaucoup."</i>
-<i>Merci</i> what now?

1745
01:06:26,449 --> 01:06:28,584
IT'S THANK YOU IN FRENCH…

1746
01:06:28,818 --> 01:06:30,553
1. DEBONE DRUMSTICKS WITH GRATITUDE

1747
01:06:30,619 --> 01:06:32,321
What's wrong with that tuile?

1748
01:06:32,388 --> 01:06:34,724
-That one shrank.
-Did it burn?

1749
01:06:34,790 --> 01:06:36,926
Chef Jong-won,
what's wrong with my tuiles?

1750
01:06:38,060 --> 01:06:39,562
-What's wrong?
-They're fine.

1751
01:06:40,129 --> 01:06:41,697
Start cooking the chicken now.

1752
01:06:41,764 --> 01:06:44,100
Wait. French recipes go step by step.

1753
01:06:44,166 --> 01:06:46,002
She says French recipes go step by step.

1754
01:06:46,068 --> 01:06:48,404
-What about salt and pepper?
-Done.

1755
01:06:48,471 --> 01:06:49,672
You actually salted it?

1756
01:06:50,673 --> 01:06:52,208
I learned to. I've improved.

1757
01:06:52,274 --> 01:06:54,310
"I've improved."

1758
01:06:55,177 --> 01:06:57,079
He's using a wok.

1759
01:06:57,146 --> 01:06:58,447
A fire show?

1760
01:06:58,514 --> 01:06:59,915
2. STIR-FRY INGREDIENTS IN A WOK

1761
01:07:00,683 --> 01:07:02,585
AN ATTEMPT TO TOSS THE WOK

1762
01:07:02,885 --> 01:07:04,820
WITH THE SPIRIT OF CHINESE CUISINE

1763
01:07:04,887 --> 01:07:06,956
-It won't catch on fire.
-It's not high enough.

1764
01:07:07,223 --> 01:07:09,525
INSTANT RICE

1765
01:07:09,592 --> 01:07:11,694
The heat needs to be much higher,

1766
01:07:11,761 --> 01:07:13,129
but he does Western cuisine, so…

1767
01:07:14,330 --> 01:07:16,966
-He's not good with the ladle.
-The ladle!

1768
01:07:17,033 --> 01:07:19,769
-He can't use the ladle too well.
-He can't.

1769
01:07:19,835 --> 01:07:21,170
SUDDENLY WORRIED ABOUT THE INFP GUY…

1770
01:07:21,837 --> 01:07:23,639
He looks awkward.

1771
01:07:24,740 --> 01:07:25,708
It won't catch on fire.

1772
01:07:26,275 --> 01:07:29,345
-He can't…
-It's supposed to catch on fire.

1773
01:07:29,412 --> 01:07:30,846
It should be on fire by now.

1774
01:07:31,113 --> 01:07:31,947
OW, THE OIL

1775
01:07:32,581 --> 01:07:33,983
STIR-FRIED INGREDIENTS, OUT

1776
01:07:34,617 --> 01:07:37,386
GRIND UP SHRIMPS

1777
01:07:37,653 --> 01:07:39,688
MIX THE STIR-FRIED INGREDIENTS
AND SHRIMPS!

1778
01:07:40,623 --> 01:07:42,191
Lao Gan Ma?

1779
01:07:42,558 --> 01:07:45,628
GRIND AND MAKE THE CHICKEN FILLING

1780
01:07:47,063 --> 01:07:48,364
INTO A PIPING BAG

1781
01:07:49,065 --> 01:07:51,233
SHOWING OFF HIS VEINS

1782
01:07:51,467 --> 01:07:52,835
THE GOOD VIBES WINDMILL

1783
01:07:52,902 --> 01:07:53,903
Can I take the bones?

1784
01:07:53,969 --> 01:07:55,871
-You can.
-Can I just take this?

1785
01:07:55,938 --> 01:07:57,106
-Yes, take it.
-Thanks.

1786
01:07:57,173 --> 01:07:58,007
HEHE

1787
01:07:58,307 --> 01:08:02,411
3. TAKE THE BONES AND PARBOIL IN WATER

1788
01:08:04,013 --> 01:08:04,980
CHICKEN STOCK, BROTH BAG

1789
01:08:06,115 --> 01:08:07,450
THE GOOD VIBES TURN

1790
01:08:07,516 --> 01:08:08,350
SCALLOPS, STAR ANISE & CLOVES

1791
01:08:08,417 --> 01:08:09,251
BAY LEAVES & CORIANDER

1792
01:08:09,318 --> 01:08:10,319
MAKING THE WONTON SOUP BROTH

1793
01:08:10,386 --> 01:08:12,321
He boiled something, right?

1794
01:08:12,388 --> 01:08:13,689
ADD PARBOILED CHICKEN BONES

1795
01:08:13,756 --> 01:08:16,892
Jong-won makes broth
with parboiled chicken.

1796
01:08:16,959 --> 01:08:18,661
"I got better too."

1797
01:08:18,727 --> 01:08:20,329
-Butter.
-Butter.

1798
01:08:20,396 --> 01:08:21,464
Parisian, butter.

1799
01:08:21,530 --> 01:08:22,865
TRANSLATION: PARISIANS USE BUTTER

1800
01:08:22,932 --> 01:08:25,134
-"Parisian, butter."
-That's a lot of butter.

1801
01:08:25,201 --> 01:08:26,802
"Parisian, butter."

1802
01:08:26,869 --> 01:08:28,437
She says whatever she wants to.

1803
01:08:28,504 --> 01:08:30,973
Why is she making fricassée in that wok?

1804
01:08:31,040 --> 01:08:32,842
You don't use high heat in French!

1805
01:08:33,109 --> 01:08:34,543
SIZZLING

1806
01:08:34,777 --> 01:08:35,644
DOESN'T EVEN PRETEND TO LISTEN

1807
01:08:35,711 --> 01:08:37,146
She added big chunks of butter.

1808
01:08:37,213 --> 01:08:39,482
-Skin down!
-Skin down!

1809
01:08:39,548 --> 01:08:41,050
Cook the skin first.

1810
01:08:41,117 --> 01:08:43,819
-Who?
-Eun-yeong.

1811
01:08:43,886 --> 01:08:46,722
You have to make the skin crispy.

1812
01:08:46,789 --> 01:08:47,656
I guess she didn't learn that.

1813
01:08:47,723 --> 01:08:48,557
<i>Bon appétit.</i>

1814
01:08:48,624 --> 01:08:50,759
-<i>Bon appétit.</i>
-Otherwise, the chicken…

1815
01:08:51,026 --> 01:08:53,095
JUST ENJOY THE DISH, PLEASE

1816
01:08:53,162 --> 01:08:55,631
She's saying French words
to remind us that it's French.

1817
01:08:55,698 --> 01:08:57,766
-Button mushrooms.
-Why do you keep using the Chinese knife?

1818
01:08:57,833 --> 01:08:59,201
The Chinese knife.

1819
01:08:59,268 --> 01:09:01,303
2. CHOP BUTTON MUSHROOMS AND SHALLOTS

1820
01:09:01,370 --> 01:09:03,405
-She keeps using the Chinese knife.
-The Chinese knife?

1821
01:09:03,472 --> 01:09:05,841
That's not the right one.

1822
01:09:05,908 --> 01:09:07,543
-How's the tuile?
-The tuile?

1823
01:09:07,610 --> 01:09:10,012
-They're too burnt.
-Are they all burnt?

1824
01:09:10,746 --> 01:09:11,847
-Turn the heat off.
-No.

1825
01:09:11,914 --> 01:09:13,849
It's okay. Just leave it there.

1826
01:09:13,916 --> 01:09:15,618
Are you using just one?

1827
01:09:15,684 --> 01:09:18,254
-Use just one.
-Okay.

1828
01:09:18,320 --> 01:09:19,154
The chicken. Quickly.

1829
01:09:19,221 --> 01:09:20,756
She cooked the chicken the wrong way.

1830
01:09:20,823 --> 01:09:22,691
-It's cooked well.
-It's cooked nicely.

1831
01:09:22,758 --> 01:09:24,927
-The bottom part turned out well.
-Yes, it looks nice.

1832
01:09:24,994 --> 01:09:26,362
She's a Parisienne.

1833
01:09:26,428 --> 01:09:28,197
-What's that?
-Lao Gan Ma!

1834
01:09:28,264 --> 01:09:29,932
That is so not fricassée!

1835
01:09:29,999 --> 01:09:32,701
There is no French dish
made with Lao Gan Ma!

1836
01:09:32,768 --> 01:09:34,737
<i>-Rosé.</i>
<i>-Rosé?</i>

1837
01:09:34,803 --> 01:09:35,638
ROSÉ

1838
01:09:37,306 --> 01:09:38,674
…IS SHE A GENIUS?

1839
01:09:39,008 --> 01:09:41,477
THE FUSION CHEF WITHOUT BORDERS

1840
01:09:41,544 --> 01:09:44,146
She's out of her mind. What's with her?

1841
01:09:44,213 --> 01:09:46,081
It looks like Chinese chili chicken!

1842
01:09:46,148 --> 01:09:48,017
She's making Chinese chili chicken!

1843
01:09:48,083 --> 01:09:49,818
-<i>Rosé</i>.
-It's Chinese chili chicken!

1844
01:09:49,885 --> 01:09:52,254
-She has to boil down wine.
-Pour it and turn the heat on.

1845
01:09:52,321 --> 01:09:54,490
-Add more wine.
-This is French.

1846
01:09:55,791 --> 01:09:56,759
That's Chinese!

1847
01:09:56,825 --> 01:09:58,127
IT LOOKS CHINESE

1848
01:09:58,194 --> 01:10:00,262
-Wine is French, though.
-It looks like a <i>mala</i> dish.

1849
01:10:00,329 --> 01:10:01,564
Seven minutes and thirty seconds.

1850
01:10:01,630 --> 01:10:04,366
-He's filling the wings.
-The wings.

1851
01:10:04,433 --> 01:10:07,536
-Eight-treasure chicken.
-Jong-won's eight-treasure chicken.

1852
01:10:07,603 --> 01:10:09,972
He's filling it with the eight treasures.

1853
01:10:10,039 --> 01:10:11,540
Seven minutes.

1854
01:10:11,607 --> 01:10:13,175
Seven minutes. You have to cook that soon.

1855
01:10:14,577 --> 01:10:15,978
-Rosemary.
-Rosemary?

1856
01:10:16,045 --> 01:10:17,680
-What?
-"Rosemary."

1857
01:10:17,746 --> 01:10:18,781
USING HER PUBERTY VOICE

1858
01:10:19,148 --> 01:10:20,049
CRUSHING GARLIC

1859
01:10:20,115 --> 01:10:21,083
AFTER CHOPPING THE GARLIC?

1860
01:10:21,150 --> 01:10:23,018
-Seven minutes.
-Garlic.

1861
01:10:23,085 --> 01:10:25,120
Why does she keep saying that?

1862
01:10:25,187 --> 01:10:26,956
"Rosemary. Garlic."

1863
01:10:27,022 --> 01:10:30,192
-Those are English words.
-"Rosemary. Garlic."

1864
01:10:30,259 --> 01:10:33,429
Jong-won is doing a better job
with the body-swapping.

1865
01:10:33,495 --> 01:10:35,331
But you have to hurry. Deep-fry them.

1866
01:10:35,397 --> 01:10:37,800
I guess he'll deep-fry the wings.

1867
01:10:37,866 --> 01:10:39,301
-Okay.
-Eight-treasure chicken.

1868
01:10:39,368 --> 01:10:40,269
That looks good.

1869
01:10:40,336 --> 01:10:42,771
-That one.
-Just like that?

1870
01:10:42,838 --> 01:10:43,872
BE CAREFUL NOT TO BREAK IT

1871
01:10:44,373 --> 01:10:46,909
I actually wanted
to name this something else.

1872
01:10:46,976 --> 01:10:48,677
It was this.

1873
01:10:48,744 --> 01:10:51,714
Hen-lo, Lee Jun-young, Don't Be a Chicken
and Try This Eight-Treasure Chicken

1874
01:10:51,780 --> 01:10:54,116
With This Wonton Soup Dish, Chick It Out.

1875
01:10:54,183 --> 01:10:56,652
AS LENGTHY
AS SUPERCALIFRAGILISTICEXPIALIDOCIOUS

1876
01:10:56,719 --> 01:10:59,388
-But I couldn't because of the topic.
-That's the original name?

1877
01:10:59,822 --> 01:11:02,124
WHAT A RELIEF IT IS

1878
01:11:02,658 --> 01:11:04,326
AMY RETRIEVES THE TUILES

1879
01:11:04,393 --> 01:11:07,529
Look at those tuiles.
All different shapes and sizes.

1880
01:11:07,796 --> 01:11:09,231
SO DIVERSE

1881
01:11:09,298 --> 01:11:12,301
The tuiles all turned out differently.
They aren't the same.

1882
01:11:12,368 --> 01:11:16,939
She must've expressed different textures
and layers in the French cuisine.

1883
01:11:17,006 --> 01:11:18,407
Diversity.

1884
01:11:18,474 --> 01:11:19,341
Diversity.

1885
01:11:19,908 --> 01:11:21,910
She's not even trying anymore.

1886
01:11:22,144 --> 01:11:24,346
SOUNDS LIKE A FRENCH WORD

1887
01:11:24,413 --> 01:11:27,549
I thought she meant chanson. "Diversity."

1888
01:11:27,616 --> 01:11:29,652
CONCERNED ABOUT THE TUILES…

1889
01:11:30,286 --> 01:11:31,720
Do you want me to make you one?

1890
01:11:31,787 --> 01:11:33,055
Thank you, Chef Jong-won.

1891
01:11:33,122 --> 01:11:34,590
<i>Merci beaucoup.</i>

1892
01:11:35,157 --> 01:11:37,693
SHE SURELY IS COURTEOUS

1893
01:11:37,760 --> 01:11:40,796
-Why do you keep saying that?
-More wine?

1894
01:11:40,863 --> 01:11:42,598
She's we…

1895
01:11:44,133 --> 01:11:45,100
She's weird.

1896
01:11:45,768 --> 01:11:48,270
SLICING RADISH!

1897
01:11:48,737 --> 01:11:52,908
He said he'd use radish
as the dumpling skin.

1898
01:11:52,975 --> 01:11:55,444
Sung-ju, can you go check the kitchen?

1899
01:11:55,511 --> 01:11:58,380
-Come with me, Ye-eun!
-Okay!

1900
01:11:58,447 --> 01:12:00,115
I'm here with Ye-eun.

1901
01:12:00,182 --> 01:12:02,451
We're here to check the kitchen.

1902
01:12:02,518 --> 01:12:04,586
First of all, this one.

1903
01:12:04,653 --> 01:12:07,056
This should be French,
but it looks a lot like Chinese.

1904
01:12:07,122 --> 01:12:08,457
Wow.

1905
01:12:08,524 --> 01:12:09,792
-Do you want to try this?
-Yes.

1906
01:12:09,858 --> 01:12:11,226
Please try it, Ye-eun.

1907
01:12:11,293 --> 01:12:12,594
So?

1908
01:12:12,661 --> 01:12:14,930
Can that turn you
into a queen in France?

1909
01:12:14,997 --> 01:12:17,199
Can you be a queen in France?

1910
01:12:18,133 --> 01:12:19,301
QUEEN YE-EUN

1911
01:12:19,868 --> 01:12:21,103
QUEEN OF PARIS

1912
01:12:22,237 --> 01:12:23,772
Really? Are you serious?

1913
01:12:23,839 --> 01:12:25,441
-It's good.
-Is it?

1914
01:12:25,507 --> 01:12:27,609
It tastes like kimchi-<i>jjigae</i>, kimchi stew.

1915
01:12:27,676 --> 01:12:29,978
-What? Wait.
-Does it?

1916
01:12:30,045 --> 01:12:32,648
-Kimchi-<i>jjigae?</i> It tastes like that.
-From that chicken?

1917
01:12:32,715 --> 01:12:34,650
It was the wine. It adds that sour note.

1918
01:12:34,717 --> 01:12:35,918
Wine.

1919
01:12:35,984 --> 01:12:37,219
Wine.

1920
01:12:37,286 --> 01:12:39,054
-Braised chicken.
-It looks like Chuncheon <i>dak-galbi</i>.

1921
01:12:39,121 --> 01:12:40,622
It must be Chongqing braised chicken.

1922
01:12:42,224 --> 01:12:45,027
Is it Chongqing braised chicken?
It does look like <i>dak-galbi.</i>

1923
01:12:45,260 --> 01:12:47,663
BETWEEN CHONGQING AND CHUNCHEON…
A DISH WITHOUT BORDERS

1924
01:12:47,730 --> 01:12:49,898
Let's move over to Chef Jong-won's side.

1925
01:12:49,965 --> 01:12:51,867
COOKED RADISH, OUT

1926
01:12:51,934 --> 01:12:54,703
He's coating radish with starch.

1927
01:12:55,270 --> 01:12:57,573
What are you filling it with?

1928
01:12:57,639 --> 01:12:59,641
What's he stuffing the radish with?

1929
01:12:59,708 --> 01:13:02,711
-The stuffing for the chicken. Yes.
-The eight-treasure chicken?

1930
01:13:02,778 --> 01:13:06,515
Jong-won makes tiny little portions.

1931
01:13:06,849 --> 01:13:08,350
NEXT, THE DEEP-FRIED WINGS

1932
01:13:09,051 --> 01:13:10,386
GOLDEN BROWN EIGHT-TREASURE CHICKEN

1933
01:13:10,452 --> 01:13:12,254
The wings look great.

1934
01:13:12,688 --> 01:13:13,522
Wow.

1935
01:13:13,589 --> 01:13:16,525
This is the broth, right? Can we try this?

1936
01:13:16,592 --> 01:13:18,761
-Please try it.
-Now.

1937
01:13:18,827 --> 01:13:22,931
Can he strike Eun-yeong out with that?

1938
01:13:22,998 --> 01:13:24,767
Will she get struck out?

1939
01:13:24,833 --> 01:13:27,169
Will she get struck out?

1940
01:13:27,236 --> 01:13:30,539
Will Eun-yeong get struck out?

1941
01:13:31,039 --> 01:13:32,674
THINKS FOR A MOMENT…

1942
01:13:32,941 --> 01:13:34,743
WE'RE GETTING EXCITED…

1943
01:13:34,810 --> 01:13:36,378
Will she get struck out?

1944
01:13:36,445 --> 01:13:38,347
Strikeout!

1945
01:13:38,414 --> 01:13:39,715
STRIKE

1946
01:13:39,782 --> 01:13:40,616
OUT!

1947
01:13:41,016 --> 01:13:42,351
A TRUE VARIETY SHOW GENIUS

1948
01:13:42,418 --> 01:13:45,788
She's a pro. She's a real professional.

1949
01:13:45,854 --> 01:13:48,123
-I agree.
-She's good.

1950
01:13:48,924 --> 01:13:51,393
CAVIAR STORED COLD

1951
01:13:52,494 --> 01:13:54,430
AMY BEGINS TO PLATE HER DISH

1952
01:13:54,496 --> 01:13:57,933
If she plates it with those tweezers,
that'll make the dish French.

1953
01:13:58,000 --> 01:13:59,635
What, tweezers equals French?

1954
01:13:59,701 --> 01:14:01,837
-She'd usually use a ladle, so…
-Right.

1955
01:14:01,904 --> 01:14:03,972
-French.
-"French."

1956
01:14:04,039 --> 01:14:05,841
-French.
-"French."

1957
01:14:05,908 --> 01:14:07,209
THE PARISIENNE CASTS A SPELL

1958
01:14:07,276 --> 01:14:09,478
The way she holds the plate
is already Chinese.

1959
01:14:09,545 --> 01:14:11,013
She's literally crazy.

1960
01:14:11,079 --> 01:14:12,247
The French language

1961
01:14:12,314 --> 01:14:14,516
is suffering greatly in this far country.

1962
01:14:14,583 --> 01:14:16,752
-May I try one?
-You may.

1963
01:14:17,419 --> 01:14:18,921
I wonder what it's like.

1964
01:14:18,987 --> 01:14:22,391
Does it taste so good
that you'd want to swap bodies?

1965
01:14:22,458 --> 01:14:24,526
Does it taste okay? Is it all right?

1966
01:14:24,593 --> 01:14:26,995
-It does!
-Yes? Does it taste French?

1967
01:14:27,062 --> 01:14:29,498
<i>Watashi wa bonjour desu!</i>

1968
01:14:29,565 --> 01:14:32,734
What's she saying?
Does it taste a bit Japanese?

1969
01:14:32,801 --> 01:14:34,336
Wait, "<i>watashi wa</i>" is Japanese.

1970
01:14:34,403 --> 01:14:36,371
-That's Japanese.
-Did it taste Japanese?

1971
01:14:36,438 --> 01:14:38,240
<i>Da jia hao.</i>

1972
01:14:38,307 --> 01:14:39,608
<i>Bonjour desu.</i>

1973
01:14:39,675 --> 01:14:43,946
I get it. It's a mix
of Japanese, Chinese, and French.

1974
01:14:44,012 --> 01:14:46,348
-It's good.
-Is it?

1975
01:14:46,715 --> 01:14:48,517
JONG-WON RETRIEVES THE WONTONS!

1976
01:14:49,818 --> 01:14:51,186
Nineteen seconds.

1977
01:14:51,253 --> 01:14:53,789
-The wontons look nice.
-You have to finish first.

1978
01:14:53,856 --> 01:14:54,957
CAVIAR

1979
01:14:56,024 --> 01:14:59,528
SHAPES IT AND PLATES IT ON A SPOON!

1980
01:14:59,862 --> 01:15:01,630
SERVING THE EIGHT-TREASURE CHICKEN

1981
01:15:02,898 --> 01:15:05,234
-How long will you burn the tuile?
-What?

1982
01:15:05,300 --> 01:15:06,969
You should've told me!

1983
01:15:07,369 --> 01:15:09,004
TOPPING THE TUILE JONG-WON MADE

1984
01:15:09,071 --> 01:15:11,540
She's topping it with caviar.

1985
01:15:11,607 --> 01:15:12,808
Why are you adding caviar?

1986
01:15:12,875 --> 01:15:14,176
French.

1987
01:15:14,476 --> 01:15:16,979
MEMORIZE THAT, "IT'S FRENCH"

1988
01:15:17,045 --> 01:15:20,849
-Lao Gan Ma and caviar?
-Will he even taste the caviar?

1989
01:15:20,916 --> 01:15:22,451
Thirteen seconds left!

1990
01:15:22,518 --> 01:15:24,920
Finish up now. Wrap it up! Ten.

1991
01:15:25,187 --> 01:15:26,154
CHOPPING GREEN ONION

1992
01:15:26,221 --> 01:15:27,723
AND ADD IT TO THE SOUP!

1993
01:15:28,123 --> 01:15:29,791
RADISH WONTON

1994
01:15:29,858 --> 01:15:31,059
-Four.
-Ring the bell.

1995
01:15:31,126 --> 01:15:33,428
-Three. Two. One.
-Three. Two. One.

1996
01:15:33,495 --> 01:15:35,197
Eun-yeong finishes!

1997
01:15:35,264 --> 01:15:36,865
Jong-won finishes too.

1998
01:15:36,932 --> 01:15:39,101
And great work, Ye-eun.

1999
01:15:39,167 --> 01:15:41,503
Jun-young, here's how you use dill.

2000
01:15:41,570 --> 01:15:43,906
-What now?
-She'll teach you how to use dill.

2001
01:15:43,972 --> 01:15:45,607
-Okay.
-How to use dill.

2002
01:15:45,674 --> 01:15:46,742
SNAP

2003
01:15:46,808 --> 01:15:48,277
-The Chinese chef's lesson.
-Nip it.

2004
01:15:48,343 --> 01:15:49,378
Top it.

2005
01:15:49,444 --> 01:15:51,113
-It's like cilantro.
-Top it?

2006
01:15:51,179 --> 01:15:53,849
<i>-Merci beaucoup.</i>
<i>-</i>"<i>Merci beaucoup</i>"?

2007
01:15:54,650 --> 01:15:58,420
THE BODY SWAP ROUND IS OVER AT LAST

2008
01:15:58,487 --> 01:16:00,322
They both finished their dishes.

2009
01:16:02,558 --> 01:16:04,326
Goodness. Great work.

2010
01:16:04,393 --> 01:16:06,862
You really seemed like a grandpa
with your hands in the back.

2011
01:16:06,929 --> 01:16:08,230
HANDS CLASPED IN THE BACK

2012
01:16:08,297 --> 01:16:09,798
Great work. Go home now.

2013
01:16:09,865 --> 01:16:13,302
EVEN SPECTATING
IS TOO MUCH FOR THE GRANDPA

2014
01:16:14,269 --> 01:16:16,305
These young ones are so diligent.

2015
01:16:16,371 --> 01:16:21,610
Both dishes were finished
with their swapped bodies.

2016
01:16:21,677 --> 01:16:24,646
First, please try the Parisienne's dish.

2017
01:16:25,047 --> 01:16:28,617
CHICKEN FRICASSÉE WITH LAO GAN MA

2018
01:16:29,785 --> 01:16:32,955
TUILE MADE BY ACCURATE MEASUREMENTS
WITH CAVIAR ON TOP

2019
01:16:34,823 --> 01:16:36,124
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S LEE JUN-YOUNG,

2020
01:16:36,191 --> 01:16:39,027
WILL YOU GIVE ME A STAR
AFTER EATING THIS, JUN-YOUNG?

2021
01:16:39,595 --> 01:16:42,097
How many tuiles did you make?
You only used one.

2022
01:16:42,164 --> 01:16:44,299
In French cuisine,

2023
01:16:44,366 --> 01:16:48,337
you make a variety of something
and pick out only the best one.

2024
01:16:48,403 --> 01:16:49,972
INTENTIONAL FRENCH DETAIL

2025
01:16:50,038 --> 01:16:51,406
How should he eat it?

2026
01:16:51,473 --> 01:16:56,011
Try the tuile, caviar,
and chicken, altogether.

2027
01:16:56,078 --> 01:16:58,614
When Ye-eun and I tried that sauce,

2028
01:16:58,680 --> 01:17:02,384
it was like a mix
of Korea, China, and France.

2029
01:17:02,451 --> 01:17:04,119
Is fricassée usually this red?

2030
01:17:04,186 --> 01:17:05,220
-Never.
-It's white.

2031
01:17:05,287 --> 01:17:06,355
-White.
-Right?

2032
01:17:06,421 --> 01:17:08,457
<i>Rosé.</i>

2033
01:17:08,523 --> 01:17:10,092
I SAID IT WAS ROSÉ

2034
01:17:10,158 --> 01:17:12,728
Is it <i>dak-galbi</i> or fricassée?
That's the problem.

2035
01:17:12,794 --> 01:17:14,696
-Somewhere near Chuncheon.
-Chongqing.

2036
01:17:14,763 --> 01:17:15,597
CAVIAR AND TUILE

2037
01:17:17,199 --> 01:17:19,368
AND A BITE OF CHONGQING STIR-FRIED CHICKEN

2038
01:17:20,135 --> 01:17:21,570
What's it like?

2039
01:17:21,637 --> 01:17:23,605
-Mala <i>jjimdak?</i>
-He thinks.

2040
01:17:23,672 --> 01:17:25,474
He doesn't respond immediately.

2041
01:17:25,540 --> 01:17:26,708
Does it taste funny?

2042
01:17:27,309 --> 01:17:28,610
First of all, it's really good.

2043
01:17:28,677 --> 01:17:31,279
It's really good? First off, it's good.

2044
01:17:31,346 --> 01:17:33,682
The chicken is very tender,

2045
01:17:33,749 --> 01:17:36,885
and I can really taste the butter.

2046
01:17:36,952 --> 01:17:38,120
But…

2047
01:17:38,387 --> 01:17:39,788
BUT?

2048
01:17:39,855 --> 01:17:41,957
…when I eat the sauce with the chili,

2049
01:17:42,024 --> 01:17:43,158
it begins

2050
01:17:43,225 --> 01:17:47,329
to taste a lot like Chinese food.

2051
01:17:47,396 --> 01:17:48,263
But still…

2052
01:17:48,330 --> 01:17:49,231
WAVING

2053
01:17:49,297 --> 01:17:51,266
Other ingredients keep that down.

2054
01:17:51,333 --> 01:17:52,901
Whenever it creeps up,

2055
01:17:52,968 --> 01:17:55,837
-it somehow goes back down.
-I see.

2056
01:17:55,904 --> 01:17:57,806
When the chili begins to rise up,

2057
01:17:57,873 --> 01:17:59,641
the load of butter fights it back.

2058
01:17:59,708 --> 01:18:02,177
-"Butter."
-"Butter."

2059
01:18:02,244 --> 01:18:04,579
It's also a bit sour because of the wine.

2060
01:18:04,646 --> 01:18:06,014
-Yes.
-I like that.

2061
01:18:06,081 --> 01:18:08,216
That sourness

2062
01:18:08,283 --> 01:18:10,585
must be coming from the wine.

2063
01:18:11,219 --> 01:18:13,188
-He's finishing it.
-He is.

2064
01:18:13,255 --> 01:18:14,289
-It's good.
-He likes to eat.

2065
01:18:14,356 --> 01:18:15,590
YUM

2066
01:18:16,892 --> 01:18:19,127
CONTINUES TO DEVOUR IT

2067
01:18:19,194 --> 01:18:21,263
Okay. He finished everything.

2068
01:18:21,329 --> 01:18:23,832
I mean, Jun-young would do that.

2069
01:18:23,899 --> 01:18:27,202
He finished everything
to show his courtesy to the chefs.

2070
01:18:27,269 --> 01:18:28,704
FULL CHEEKS

2071
01:18:28,770 --> 01:18:31,506
Korean, Chinese, and French.

2072
01:18:31,573 --> 01:18:32,941
Which is it closest to?

2073
01:18:34,543 --> 01:18:35,644
SIGH…

2074
01:18:36,344 --> 01:18:38,480
-Koreatown in France?
-Or Seorae Village?

2075
01:18:38,547 --> 01:18:40,549
-There's no Korea here.
-No Korea.

2076
01:18:40,615 --> 01:18:42,117
RELIEVED

2077
01:18:42,184 --> 01:18:44,986
-I think there is Korea, though.
-Why?

2078
01:18:45,053 --> 01:18:47,589
I'd fall asleep while hiding
in my grandma's perilla leaf farm.

2079
01:18:47,656 --> 01:18:49,257
And her place was in Chuncheon.

2080
01:18:49,324 --> 01:18:53,228
She'd grab my hand,
take me back home for dinner,

2081
01:18:53,295 --> 01:18:54,896
and make me <i>dak-galbi </i>just like that one.

2082
01:18:55,130 --> 01:18:56,298
FITS RIGHT IN

2083
01:18:56,364 --> 01:18:57,733
He even attacks his opponents.

2084
01:18:57,966 --> 01:18:58,967
HIS CHARACTER HAS CHANGED TOO

2085
01:18:59,034 --> 01:19:00,469
They swapped.

2086
01:19:00,535 --> 01:19:03,338
-He's still swapped with Eun-yeong.
-He's channeling her.

2087
01:19:03,405 --> 01:19:05,507
Their bodies are still swapped.

2088
01:19:05,574 --> 01:19:07,843
Next, Park Eun-yeong! Strikeout!

2089
01:19:07,909 --> 01:19:09,644
RADISH WONTON SOUP

2090
01:19:09,711 --> 01:19:11,947
CAVIAR

2091
01:19:12,514 --> 01:19:14,716
EIGHT-TREASURE CHICKEN

2092
01:19:15,650 --> 01:19:19,988
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
PARK EUN-YEONG! STRIKEOUT!

2093
01:19:20,055 --> 01:19:22,457
-Everything looks so neat.
-Yes.

2094
01:19:22,524 --> 01:19:24,693
Eight-treasure chicken and wonton soup.

2095
01:19:24,760 --> 01:19:26,261
Whoa.

2096
01:19:26,328 --> 01:19:27,863
Is caviar used in Chinese cuisine?

2097
01:19:27,929 --> 01:19:30,132
They do in classy restaurants.

2098
01:19:30,198 --> 01:19:31,333
OF COURSE

2099
01:19:31,399 --> 01:19:32,601
Even the silk merchant.

2100
01:19:32,667 --> 01:19:35,437
-Silk merchant?
-Mr. Wang the silk merchant?

2101
01:19:35,504 --> 01:19:38,140
Mr. Son the silk merchant.
We'll give you that.

2102
01:19:38,206 --> 01:19:39,775
How do I eat this?

2103
01:19:39,841 --> 01:19:42,811
-First, try a bite of the chicken wing.
-Chicken wing.

2104
01:19:42,878 --> 01:19:45,547
What were the eight ingredients?

2105
01:19:45,614 --> 01:19:46,782
Pancetta.

2106
01:19:46,848 --> 01:19:47,749
Shrimp.

2107
01:19:47,816 --> 01:19:49,317
Dried scallop.

2108
01:19:49,384 --> 01:19:51,553
LAO GAN MA, ONION, SHIITAKE,
INSTANT RICE, MINCED GINGER

2109
01:19:51,620 --> 01:19:53,588
<i>You added lots of ingredients.</i>

2110
01:19:53,655 --> 01:19:55,524
-Eight-treasure chicken.
-What's it like?

2111
01:19:56,458 --> 01:19:57,392
In one bite.

2112
01:19:59,127 --> 01:20:01,163
He had already deboned those.

2113
01:20:01,229 --> 01:20:02,564
Deboned chicken wings

2114
01:20:02,631 --> 01:20:04,432
-are the definition of luxury.
-Yes.

2115
01:20:04,499 --> 01:20:06,935
Jun-young eats it with a straight face.

2116
01:20:07,002 --> 01:20:07,903
It's so good.

2117
01:20:07,969 --> 01:20:09,805
-It's so good?
-It looks good.

2118
01:20:09,871 --> 01:20:13,875
I love how the coating is so thin.
That's how I like it.

2119
01:20:13,942 --> 01:20:18,547
I usually prefer something
with a lighter coating like <i>karaage</i>.

2120
01:20:18,613 --> 01:20:20,415
So it's really delicious.

2121
01:20:20,482 --> 01:20:23,018
Can you taste what he filled it with?

2122
01:20:23,084 --> 01:20:24,519
You can taste one at a time

2123
01:20:24,586 --> 01:20:25,620
as you continue to chew.

2124
01:20:26,188 --> 01:20:27,622
He mentioned treasures before,

2125
01:20:27,689 --> 01:20:29,891
and it really is like treasure hunting.

2126
01:20:29,958 --> 01:20:31,593
I'd notice dried scallops,

2127
01:20:31,660 --> 01:20:34,095
then something else
after spotting that one.

2128
01:20:34,162 --> 01:20:36,631
And then, some pancetta. It's a wonder.

2129
01:20:37,532 --> 01:20:39,167
He's tasting so many ingredients.

2130
01:20:39,234 --> 01:20:41,570
-He filled it with fillings.
-Eight ingredients.

2131
01:20:41,636 --> 01:20:43,705
The whole thing at once.

2132
01:20:43,772 --> 01:20:45,307
-Such a classy dish.
-It is.

2133
01:20:45,373 --> 01:20:47,676
That's actually a teacup.

2134
01:20:47,742 --> 01:20:49,344
Pick it up, sip the broth,

2135
01:20:49,411 --> 01:20:51,713
use the spoon with the caviar,

2136
01:20:51,780 --> 01:20:54,916
-and have it with wonton.
-Caviar and wonton?

2137
01:20:54,983 --> 01:20:57,052
First, the clear wonton soup.

2138
01:20:57,619 --> 01:20:58,887
SLURP

2139
01:20:58,954 --> 01:21:01,590
It's the perfect time
to have a soup like that.

2140
01:21:02,457 --> 01:21:03,391
Whoa.

2141
01:21:03,458 --> 01:21:05,327
-That's it.
-What is it?

2142
01:21:05,527 --> 01:21:06,461
MOVED

2143
01:21:06,528 --> 01:21:08,463
It's really like the soup
for wonton noodles.

2144
01:21:08,530 --> 01:21:09,731
Does it taste like wonton soup?

2145
01:21:09,798 --> 01:21:10,966
What did you use?

2146
01:21:11,032 --> 01:21:14,703
He had lots of spices,
so I used star anise and even coriander.

2147
01:21:14,769 --> 01:21:17,239
That soup didn't even take 15 minutes.

2148
01:21:17,839 --> 01:21:18,807
Whoa.

2149
01:21:18,874 --> 01:21:21,109
See? Your reactions are bigger
after the five-minute check with me.

2150
01:21:21,176 --> 01:21:22,544
You're right.

2151
01:21:23,044 --> 01:21:24,646
It was effective.

2152
01:21:24,713 --> 01:21:27,282
That was the biggest sound he made
over the last two episodes.

2153
01:21:27,983 --> 01:21:29,951
THIS TIME, WITH THE CAVIAR

2154
01:21:30,018 --> 01:21:32,020
Make a bigger sound.

2155
01:21:32,087 --> 01:21:33,121
TRYING NOT TO LAUGH

2156
01:21:33,555 --> 01:21:34,856
SLURP

2157
01:21:35,290 --> 01:21:36,124
WHAT'S IT LIKE WITH CAVIAR?

2158
01:21:36,191 --> 01:21:37,792
I wonder what that's like.

2159
01:21:37,859 --> 01:21:40,996
I always found caviar
to be difficult to use

2160
01:21:41,062 --> 01:21:42,797
because it was a bit too fishy for me.

2161
01:21:43,832 --> 01:21:46,334
But it's not fishy at all
when I eat it like this.

2162
01:21:46,401 --> 01:21:48,003
Because of the spices.

2163
01:21:48,069 --> 01:21:49,671
With the soup.

2164
01:21:49,738 --> 01:21:51,273
What's the radish wonton like?

2165
01:21:51,339 --> 01:21:53,375
It tastes like regular dumplings.

2166
01:21:53,441 --> 01:21:55,844
I can't even tell
that it's made with radish.

2167
01:21:56,578 --> 01:21:59,915
I love this soup the most.

2168
01:21:59,981 --> 01:22:01,016
I see.

2169
01:22:01,583 --> 01:22:03,618
It really feels like Hong Kong.

2170
01:22:03,685 --> 01:22:05,654
He says it feels like Hong Kong.

2171
01:22:05,720 --> 01:22:07,155
That's your second hometown.

2172
01:22:07,222 --> 01:22:09,324
I'm going there again this week.

2173
01:22:09,391 --> 01:22:12,227
I see. Forget San Francisco.

2174
01:22:12,294 --> 01:22:14,930
He just downed that soup.

2175
01:22:14,996 --> 01:22:16,498
He won-downed the wonton soup.

2176
01:22:16,564 --> 01:22:17,966
He has nothing more to eat.

2177
01:22:18,033 --> 01:22:20,035
-That was delicious.
-Yes.

2178
01:22:20,835 --> 01:22:22,871
CLEARED BOTH DISHES

2179
01:22:22,938 --> 01:22:26,174
You have to make the final decision.

2180
01:22:26,241 --> 01:22:28,977
<i>Press one for Chef Jong-won,</i>

2181
01:22:29,044 --> 01:22:31,112
<i>and two for Chef Eun-yeong.</i>

2182
01:22:31,179 --> 01:22:33,848
Make your decision and press the button!

2183
01:22:34,916 --> 01:22:37,452
FINISHED CHOOSING

2184
01:22:37,519 --> 01:22:40,855
Which one of them was chosen?

2185
01:22:40,922 --> 01:22:42,691
Let's find out!

2186
01:22:42,757 --> 01:22:43,858
Show us!

2187
01:22:44,526 --> 01:22:47,095
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Office Body Swap.

2188
01:22:47,162 --> 01:22:50,165
Chef Eun-yeong made a French dish,

2189
01:22:50,231 --> 01:22:53,034
and Chef Jong-won made Chinese food.

2190
01:22:53,101 --> 01:22:55,837
Whose body swap was more effective?

2191
01:22:55,904 --> 01:22:58,640
Who did Jun-young choose?

2192
01:22:59,140 --> 01:23:01,209
Who's going to take the star?

2193
01:23:01,276 --> 01:23:03,878
Who's going to take the star?

2194
01:23:04,079 --> 01:23:05,513
SON JONG-WON WINS

2195
01:23:05,580 --> 01:23:06,581
Son Jong-won wins.

2196
01:23:06,881 --> 01:23:09,017
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
PARK EUN-YEONG! STRIKEOUT! WINS

2197
01:23:09,084 --> 01:23:10,518
The winner is Jong-won.

2198
01:23:10,585 --> 01:23:12,821
Jong-won just struck Eun-yeong out.

2199
01:23:12,887 --> 01:23:14,889
-He beat her with Poong's knife.
-With my knife!

2200
01:23:14,956 --> 01:23:16,825
-I can't believe it worked.
-It did.

2201
01:23:16,891 --> 01:23:18,126
Was there a difference?

2202
01:23:18,193 --> 01:23:21,463
Of course, both dishes were delicious.

2203
01:23:21,529 --> 01:23:23,631
I can't judge which is better.

2204
01:23:23,698 --> 01:23:25,934
-But he seemed more immersed
-He looked for it.

2205
01:23:26,001 --> 01:23:27,402
in the body-swap theme.

2206
01:23:27,469 --> 01:23:30,238
That was why I chose him.

2207
01:23:30,305 --> 01:23:33,475
Chef Jong-won, you tried making Chinese.
What was that like?

2208
01:23:33,541 --> 01:23:35,310
The moment I said the dish name,

2209
01:23:35,377 --> 01:23:36,845
I knew I was going to need

2210
01:23:36,911 --> 01:23:38,246
at least a month to recover.

2211
01:23:39,447 --> 01:23:41,349
I thought I'd be ill for that long,

2212
01:23:41,416 --> 01:23:44,686
but I think it'll be just a week,
thanks to you choosing me.

2213
01:23:44,753 --> 01:23:48,490
So what did you do to Park Eun-yeong?

2214
01:23:49,090 --> 01:23:50,291
SIGH…

2215
01:23:50,358 --> 01:23:51,292
Do it one last time!

2216
01:23:51,359 --> 01:23:52,227
The name of your dish!

2217
01:23:52,293 --> 01:23:54,362
-Can you do it with me?
-Okay, let's do it together.

2218
01:23:54,429 --> 01:23:56,731
-What now?
-What happened to her?

2219
01:23:56,798 --> 01:23:59,200
Park Eun-yeong! Strikeout!

2220
01:23:59,267 --> 01:24:02,337
That's it. That was great.

2221
01:24:02,404 --> 01:24:03,772
Yes.

2222
01:24:03,838 --> 01:24:06,341
He keeps first place alone.

2223
01:24:06,408 --> 01:24:08,176
He now has nine stars!

2224
01:24:08,243 --> 01:24:09,344
STAY TUNED FOR THE PREVIEW

2225
01:24:09,411 --> 01:24:11,312
Congratulations, Jong-won!

2226
01:24:12,747 --> 01:24:14,716
Please welcome the fridge owners

2227
01:24:14,783 --> 01:24:17,285
for the 2026 World Cup Special! Welcome!

2228
01:24:17,352 --> 01:24:18,386
<i>The heroes of the World Cup.</i>

2229
01:24:18,453 --> 01:24:19,854
He shows it off and says that

2230
01:24:19,921 --> 01:24:22,657
he knows all the chefs, so I can ask him
when I want to eat somewhere.

2231
01:24:22,924 --> 01:24:23,758
ACCUSING HIS BIG TALK

2232
01:24:23,825 --> 01:24:24,692
Me?

2233
01:24:24,759 --> 01:24:26,761
It killed my pride a little.

2234
01:24:26,828 --> 01:24:29,230
He said it was only possible through him.

2235
01:24:29,531 --> 01:24:30,965
EXPOSING JUNG-HWAN'S TRUE NATURE

2236
01:24:31,032 --> 01:24:33,034
I heard you analyzed
the problem with <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

2237
01:24:33,101 --> 01:24:35,804
-I think he's been here for too long.
-Hey!

2238
01:24:35,870 --> 01:24:38,506
I came here to recommend Hang-seo
for that position.

2239
01:24:38,773 --> 01:24:40,175
THE SENIOR PLAYERS CAME FOR HIS JOB

2240
01:24:40,408 --> 01:24:41,543
HIS GREATEST CRISIS

2241
01:24:42,110 --> 01:24:43,445
Thank you.

2242
01:24:43,678 --> 01:24:44,646
PERFECT TEAMWORK

2243
01:24:44,712 --> 01:24:46,681
Can you sub for me just for this episode?

2244
01:24:46,748 --> 01:24:48,917
-This is awkward.
-It must be.

2245
01:24:49,217 --> 01:24:51,619
WHAT IS YOUR OUTLOOK
FOR THE 2026 WORLD CUP?

2246
01:24:51,686 --> 01:24:54,889
If I may leave a request for Manager Hong…

2247
01:24:54,956 --> 01:24:55,857
Yes?

2248
01:24:55,924 --> 01:24:59,027
Our national soccer team
is playing at a high level.

2249
01:24:59,094 --> 01:25:00,161
First of all…

2250
01:25:00,228 --> 01:25:02,530
WHAT DOES HANG-SEO THINK WE SHOULD GO FOR?

2251
01:25:02,864 --> 01:25:04,466
WHAT DO THESE SOCCER LEGENDS PREDICT?

2252
01:25:04,532 --> 01:25:06,868
<i>A Vietnamese dish</i>
<i>to capture Manager Park's appetite.</i>

2253
01:25:06,935 --> 01:25:08,603
-I'm seeing Vietnamese ingredients.
-And lots.

2254
01:25:08,670 --> 01:25:10,105
People do this in Vietnamese cuisine.

2255
01:25:10,171 --> 01:25:11,739
It smells like Hanoi.

2256
01:25:11,806 --> 01:25:13,341
He just swallowed hard.

2257
01:25:13,408 --> 01:25:14,642
I keep drooling.

2258
01:25:14,709 --> 01:25:16,044
He keeps going back for more.

2259
01:25:16,111 --> 01:25:17,312
It's good.

2260
01:25:18,413 --> 01:25:19,581
We're here with someone amazing.

2261
01:25:19,647 --> 01:25:21,916
<i>I'm here to slash everything away.</i>

2262
01:25:22,217 --> 01:25:23,952
THE WITCH WITH A WOK SLASHES AWAY

2263
01:25:24,152 --> 01:25:25,019
THE GODDESS FIGHTS BACK

2264
01:25:25,353 --> 01:25:26,287
PARK EUN-YEONG IS NOT AN EASY FIGHT

2265
01:25:26,521 --> 01:25:28,256
A BIG MATCH
BETWEEN THE INDUSTRY COLLEAGUES

2266
01:25:28,990 --> 01:25:30,125
SPIRIT CHANNELING

2267
01:25:30,558 --> 01:25:31,826
A LITERAL KNIFE DANCE

2268
01:25:31,893 --> 01:25:33,094
Let's go!

2269
01:25:33,394 --> 01:25:35,630
A SUDDEN GUT RITUAL BREAKS OUT

2270
01:25:36,131 --> 01:25:37,565
WHO'LL RISE AS THE TRUE MADWOMAN?

2271
01:25:38,199 --> 01:25:40,235
<i>I guess Chinese cuisine has to be scary.</i>

2272
01:25:40,969 --> 01:25:42,871
Who stares at people eating like that?

2273
01:25:42,937 --> 01:25:44,772
How's he going to eat in peace?

2274
01:25:55,250 --> 01:26:00,021
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
